<paragraph id="AA1F5F3EEFE098B94F2EAAF166940891" pageNumber="7">
<taxonomicName id="FC0E000199022CBB015745FBD66A7046" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:225CA58F-2A6D-43EE-80D7-6A05F7A05273" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon mona Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:7" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mona">Symphysanodon mona</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6F850C0CAA9447868F24A49C15F2997D" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="26286450E987CB6C68448CF3FE7FAE30" pageNumber="7">Akarnax Slopefish</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A62D2D1E5B9A115F8E1AC5BBBCC08C5F" type="description">
<paragraph id="1602D6AB5B7321DBF6518C1A48EDBE59" pageNumber="7">(Figures 1-4; Tables 1, 8, 9)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F21DA66A251D36D1081E5EB07FD75888" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="0DE67A20BBE7CF962520F6F9DDD925C6" pageNumber="7">Holotype: USNM 371386, 86 mm SL; Mona Passage, off the west coast of Puerto Rico; 18°13’ N, 67°20’ W; 384 m; OREGON station 2645; 5 October 1959.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0D1BDC04AAADFD76EE989E11CB0CB2E" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E093CD045F72E2913A23A8A93537CC79" lastPageNumber="8" pageNumber="7">
Diagnosis. A species of 
<taxonomicName id="297E39D9A38CDA0CE0645B0B860599DA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F334D443-843F-494A-AC1A-947DDCBACA9F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon Bleeker 1878:60" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Symphysanodon</taxonomicName>
(Figure 1) distinguishable from all other species of the genus in having fewer gillrakers on first arch (4 or 5 + 19-21 = 24 or 25 total vs. 8-14 + 20-29 = 28-42 total). In addition, it differs from other Atlantic species in having a ventral branch of obliquus dorsalis 3 muscle (Figure 2, vs. its absence in the other two species) and in having a posteriorly projecting extension of the cartilaginous lateral end of ceratobranchial 4 (Figure 3A, vs. its absence in the other two species; 
<taxonomicName id="7601B07DF0F585DAE19B4BA21FEF105F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10736DBF-680B-4D45-ADDA-A63828ACEF46" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon berryi Anderson 1970:338" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="berryi">S. berryi</taxonomicName>
has a small accessory cartilage, Figure 3B, associated with the lateral end of ceratobranchial 4; the specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="464F726EE63357DD862A1F97797215D9" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FD071F4D-6E27-4C46-9748-FE5832F8C79C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon octoactinus Anderson 1970:342" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="octoactinus">S. octoactinus</taxonomicName>
examined may have had a very small accessory cartilage that was lost during dissection).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D921A1185987F14B729D529109FD3944" type="description">
<paragraph id="16AAD1474C9330BBDE092FE98E1D80B4" lastPageNumber="9" pageNumber="8">
Description. The characters included in the combined description of 
<taxonomicName id="4EA0A05C41541A375C10C226F594CDC8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:225CA58F-2A6D-43EE-80D7-6A05F7A05273" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon mona Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:7" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mona">S. mona</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DA74444C118A224C6B85D1B43C4F819D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A50F8091-80D6-415D-8AAE-6DA1E0C34A6F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon parini Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:11" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parini">S. parini</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="F4A94F5AA980A5243AB54BEAAF3F494B" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:29BB4082-BB0D-48A2-8FDD-919107F1B13F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon rhax Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:16" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rhax">S. rhax</taxonomicName>
and those presented in the species diagnosis form part of the species description. Tubed scales in lateral line ca. 47 (many missing). Dorsal-fin rays IX, 10. Pectoral-fin rays 17. Procurrent caudal-fin rays 13 dorsally, 12 ventrally. Trisegmental pterygiophores: 3 associated with dorsal fin, 2 with anal fin. Epineurals associated with first 9 vertebrae. Uroneurals probably 2 pairs, not seen clearly on radiograph. (Johnson, 1984, reported 2 uroneurals for the genus and found 2 in a 15-mm cleared and stained larva of another species of 
<taxonomicName id="5650209B473B929E5257AB4A5E1D3BE0" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F334D443-843F-494A-AC1A-947DDCBACA9F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon Bleeker 1878:60" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Symphysanodon</taxonomicName>
, pers. comm. 21 February 2003, and we found 2 uroneurals in radiographed specimens of each of the other species in the genus.) Internarial distance contained ca. 5 times in snout length. Pelvic fins and both caudal-fin lobes damaged; measurements of other body parts are presented in percentages of SL in Table 1.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6BA7BA3E1F08987418213A0EBB05B2E4" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="30E1F6948676535959F547EFA907865A" pageNumber="10">
Comparisons of Atlantic species of 
<taxonomicName id="080854E406A9502252C6AC3D7A899551" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F334D443-843F-494A-AC1A-947DDCBACA9F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon Bleeker 1878:60" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Symphysanodon</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="190DD6F4F71AE5F1DA0E2D2CA09BC3E8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:225CA58F-2A6D-43EE-80D7-6A05F7A05273" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon mona Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:7" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mona">Symphysanodon mona</taxonomicName>
is easily distinguished from the other Atlantic 
<taxonomicName id="0CFAA86881B93267AEF3A5720C2BD7EA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F334D443-843F-494A-AC1A-947DDCBACA9F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon Bleeker 1878:60" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Symphysanodon</taxonomicName>
on the basis of gillraker counts: 
<taxonomicName id="354188DB3172C0D6100F011F8217DCD9" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:225CA58F-2A6D-43EE-80D7-6A05F7A05273" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon mona Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:7" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mona">S mona</taxonomicName>
with 4 or 5 + 19-21 = 24 or 25 total; 
<taxonomicName id="703631BA6C12A57810D46AC3632EF890" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10736DBF-680B-4D45-ADDA-A63828ACEF46" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon berryi Anderson 1970:338" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="berryi">S. berryi</taxonomicName>
with 9-12 + 24-28 = 34-39 total; 
<taxonomicName id="5BAE30E9789C15AB5DA341CEA90AD95E" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FD071F4D-6E27-4C46-9748-FE5832F8C79C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon octoactinus Anderson 1970:342" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="octoactinus">S. octoactinus</taxonomicName>
with 12-14 + 26-29 = 38-42 total. Selected morphometric data for the Atlantic species of 
<taxonomicName id="A6BAF12BF2EFC6305F76B33B18D726A5" genus="Symphysandon" pageNumber="10" rank="genus">Symphysandon</taxonomicName>
are compared in Table 1. In addition there are notable differences among the Atlantic species in the musculature and skeleton of the branchial region (see Figures 2 &amp; 3). 
<taxonomicName id="938FE94BCDE89871F03A0D7BECF79D02" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:225CA58F-2A6D-43EE-80D7-6A05F7A05273" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon mona Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:7" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mona">Symphysanodon mona</taxonomicName>
has a ventral branch of the obliquus dorsalis 3 muscle (Figure 2, vs. its absence in the other two Atlantic species) and has a posteriorly projecting fingerlike extension of the cartilaginous lateral end of ceratobranchial 4 (Figure 3A, vs. its absence in the other Atlantic species; 
<taxonomicName id="FA8D2B0744CF5FC610C728A5768FBEF6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10736DBF-680B-4D45-ADDA-A63828ACEF46" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon berryi Anderson 1970:338" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="berryi">S. berryi</taxonomicName>
has a small accessory cartilage, Figure 3B, associated with the lateral end of ceratobranchial 4, which is not present in 
<taxonomicName id="5F6BCACB5D3DC7C051837BF077F64315" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:225CA58F-2A6D-43EE-80D7-6A05F7A05273" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon mona Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:7" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mona">S. mona</taxonomicName>
and was not observed in 
<taxonomicName id="E985D91FDA57A47DDE9CB9633906A8B4" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FD071F4D-6E27-4C46-9748-FE5832F8C79C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon octoactinus Anderson 1970:342" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="octoactinus">S. octoactinus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5055E6E7C27735F560F608D996579C24" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0D044D60D834275724AE3B3D8C551364" pageNumber="10">
Distribution. Known only from the type locality: Mona Passage off the west coast of Puerto Rico in 384 m (see Figure 4). The holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="622EB2E1A7CD536336508F11FF434C66" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:225CA58F-2A6D-43EE-80D7-6A05F7A05273" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon mona Anderson &amp; Springer 2005:7" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mona">S. mona</taxonomicName>
was collected with a specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="0ABB856309FD96C767A0DF34C11E15CC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10736DBF-680B-4D45-ADDA-A63828ACEF46" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon berryi Anderson 1970:338" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="berryi">S. berryi</taxonomicName>
(USNM 289922).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A0E963CE3D3039886D1954F216610B31" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0E6FAF01F617B86384FFF6543AB3ADEF" pageNumber="10">
Etymology. The name mona refers to the type locality (Mona Passage) and is a feminine noun in apposition to 
<taxonomicName id="96CCBBAB08ADF73E5923A9AFA673836D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F334D443-843F-494A-AC1A-947DDCBACA9F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon Bleeker 1878:60" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Symphysanodon</taxonomicName>
. The common name Akarnax Slopefish is derived from a Greek word meaning “a basslike fish” and from the fact that species of 
<taxonomicName id="4CB75DE08A9325950C4387861630A1F4" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F334D443-843F-494A-AC1A-947DDCBACA9F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Symphysanodontidae" genus="Symphysanodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Symphysanodon Bleeker 1878:60" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Symphysanodon</taxonomicName>
have been collected frequently in slope waters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
